---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="snn — spiking networks as convex optimizers">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">

    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="pt-6 pb-16 border-b border-[--color-rule]">
      <p class="uppercase tracking-widest text-xs text-[--color-accent] mb-4">
        a friendly tour
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl leading-tight mb-6">
        Spiking neural networks <em>are</em> convex optimizers.
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-[--color-muted] mb-8 max-w-2xl">
        A simple population of leaky integrate-and-fire neurons, with the right
        connectivity, solves a quadratic program. Each spike is a constraint
        becoming active. Each silence is a gradient step. The page below walks
        through the idea, the math, and a runnable Python implementation —
        for students, curious researchers, and anyone who likes when two
        fields turn out to be the same field.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href="/intro/"
          class="inline-block px-4 py-2 rounded-md bg-[--color-accent] text-white no-underline text-sm font-medium"
        >
          Start with the intuition →
        </a>
        <a
          href="https://github.com/ahkhan03/SNN_opt"
          class="inline-block px-4 py-2 rounded-md border border-[--color-rule] text-[--color-fg] no-underline text-sm font-medium"
        >
          View <code class="bg-transparent">snn_opt</code> on GitHub
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The idea, in three beats -->
    <section class="py-16 border-b border-[--color-rule]">
      <h2 class="text-2xl mb-6">The idea, in three beats</h2>

      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
        <div>
          <p class="text-[--color-accent] font-semibold mb-2">1. Drift</p>
          <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Between spikes, each neuron's membrane voltage moves by the
            gradient of an objective. This is plain gradient descent —
            dressed up as biology.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-[--color-accent] font-semibold mb-2">2. Spike</p>
          <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-sm leading-relaxed">
            When the voltage would push the trajectory past a constraint,
            a spike fires. The spike re-projects the state onto the
            feasible boundary — a discrete correction.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-[--color-accent] font-semibold mb-2">3. Settle</p>
          <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-sm leading-relaxed">
            The spike train and the drift balance at the constrained
            optimum. The active spikes encode the active constraint set.
            The math is exactly that of a primal-dual QP solver.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The picture -->
    <section class="py-16 border-b border-[--color-rule]">
      <h2 class="text-2xl mb-3">The picture</h2>
      <p class="text-[--color-muted] mb-6">
        A 4-D quadratic, optimum outside a box constraint. The trajectory
        bounces against the four "active" faces every iteration; each dot
        is one projection event.
      </p>
      <figure class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-[--color-rule] bg-white">
        <img
          src="/figures/02_spike_raster.png"
          alt="Projection-spike raster on a 4-D box-constrained QP"
          class="w-full h-auto"
        />
        <figcaption class="px-4 py-3 text-xs text-[--color-muted] border-t border-[--color-rule]">
          Top: spike raster, one row per inequality, dot size ∝ projection
          magnitude. Bottom: objective gap on the same iteration axis.
          Generated by <code>benchmarks/02_spike_raster.py</code>.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- What's here -->
    <section class="py-16 border-b border-[--color-rule]">
      <h2 class="text-2xl mb-6">What you'll find here</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-4">
        <li>
          <a href="/intro/" class="font-medium">Intro</a>
          <span class="text-[--color-muted]"> — the spiking idea
          explained from scratch, with no prior neuromorphic background
          required.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/tutorials/" class="font-medium">Tutorials</a>
          <span class="text-[--color-muted]"> — hands-on walkthroughs:
          formulating SVMs, ridge regression, PCA and a few control
          problems as QPs you can drop into the solver.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/papers/" class="font-medium">Papers</a>
          <span class="text-[--color-muted]"> — the published work that
          uses this framework, with abstracts and DOI links.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://github.com/ahkhan03/SNN_opt" class="font-medium">
            <code>snn_opt</code> on GitHub
          </a>
          <span class="text-[--color-muted]"> — the canonical Python
          implementation: solver, examples, benchmarks, full mathematical
          writeup.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- For whom -->
    <section class="py-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl mb-4">Who this is for</h2>
      <p class="text-[--color-muted] mb-3">
        Students starting a thesis on neuromorphic methods. Researchers
        from optimization or control who heard "spiking networks" and
        weren't sure what to make of it. Anyone who finds beauty in
        connections between fields that look unrelated until they don't.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[--color-muted]">
        If you want the formal version: head to the
        <a href="https://github.com/ahkhan03/SNN_opt"><code>snn_opt</code> repository</a>
        — it has the full theory document, an academic-style README, and
        a benchmark suite. The pages here are the <em>friendly</em>
        version of that material.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>
